<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910117-0039</DOCNO><DOCID>910117-0039.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- ASK Corp.:   Company, President Settle   Securities Violation Lawsuit</HL><DATE>01/17/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   ASKCD</CO><IN>HOME ELECTRONICS, FURNISHINGS, APPLIANCES (HMF)BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)SECURITIES REGULATIONS AND ENFORCEMENTS (RGU)</IN><GV>SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)</GV><LP>   ASK Corp., Waco, Texas, said it and its president settleda lawsuit filed against them by the Securities and ExchangeCommission, charging securities-law violations.   The SEC sued ASK in July 1989, charging that the companyreported misleading financial information betweeen 1982 and1985. The SEC charged, among other things, that ASK, whichthen was known as American Solar King, booked profits fromsales of solar-power systems before they were installed.</LP><TEXT>   ASK, an alternative-energy concern, said it didn't admitor deny the allegations, but settled with the SEC to putlitigation behind it. The company, which is short of cash,said recently that it might have to convert its Chapter 11bankruptcy-reorganization proceeding to a Chapter 7liquidation proceeding if it can't raise capital soon.</TEXT></DOC>